            <!-- Contents -->
            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">Commentary by IA himself on his cycle of love poetry,
                     Tarjumān al-Ashwāq (RG 767), bringing out the esoteric meaning of the verses.
                     As IA explains in the preface, he wrote it at the request of Badr al-Ḥabashī
                     and Ibn Sawdakīn in Aleppo in 611H because it had incited the disapproval of
                     some of the local ʿulamāʾ.</note>
               <note type="structure"/>
               <note type="contentsNote"/>
            </noteGrp>
            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">A much copied work, verified by two historic mss., Evkaf
                  Muzesi 1713 (873H) and Fatih 5322 (934H), which are both copied from originals
                  written by Ayyūb b. Badr, with samāʿ dated 626H and 616H resp. Most mss. also
                  include the full text of the Tarjuman (RG 767), of which there are also some
                  separate copies. Copy in Baghdad, Iraq Museum 11086/2 which a cataloguer believed
                  was copied in the 7th century (al-Furqān online:
                  https://www.al-furqan.com/our_is_item/manid/1250158/groupid/139348) See: مخطوطات
                  الأدب في المتحف العراقي = Makhṭūṭāt al-adab fī al-Matḥaf al-ʿIrāqī = Catalogue of
                  Manuscripts of Literature In the Iraq Museum Library, p.444 (#1155). After
                  transcribing the usual text in which IA gives the reason he wrote the work the
                  catalogue has this: فرغ منه المؤلف سنة 614H بمدرسة الامير مظفر الدين محمود This
                  information does not occur in most mss: completed 614H in the madrasah of Amīr
                  Muẓaffar al-dīn Maḥmūd. (It occurs in the Shuqayrī edition of 1995).</note>
